< li > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Christof_Koch" OreVar = "Christof Koch" > Koch , Christof < /a > , "Proust among the Machines" , < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Scientific_American" OreVar = "Scientific American" > Scientific American < /a > < /i > , vol. 321 , no. 6 ( OreVar 2019 ) , pp.&#160 ; 46–49. < a OreVar = "/wiki/Christof_Koch" OreVar = "Christof Koch" > Christof Koch < /a > doubts the possibility of "intelligent" machines attaining < a OreVar = "/wiki/Consciousness" OreVar = "Consciousness" > consciousness < /a > , because "[e]ven the most sophisticated < a OreVar = "/wiki/Brain_simulation" OreVar = "Brain simulation" > brain simulations < /a > are unlikely to produce conscious < a OreVar = "/wiki/Feelings" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Feelings" > feelings < /a > ." ( OreVar ; 48. ) According to Koch , "Whether machines can become < a OreVar = "/wiki/Sentience" OreVar = "Sentience" > sentient < /a > [is important] for < a OreVar = "/wiki/Ethics" OreVar = "Ethics" > ethical < /a > reasons. If computers experience life through their own senses , they cease to be purely a means to an end determined by their usefulness to... humans. Per GNW [the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Global_Workspace_Theory#Global_neuronal_workspace" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Global Workspace Theory" > Global Neuronal Workspace < /a > theory] , they turn from mere objects into subjects... with a < a OreVar = OreDef ( philosophy ) " OreVar = "Point of view ( OreVar ) " > point of view < /a > .... Once computers' < a OreVar = "/wiki/Cognitive_abilities" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Cognitive abilities" > cognitive abilities < /a > rival those of humanity , their impulse to push for legal and political < a OreVar = "/wiki/Rights" OreVar = "Rights" > rights < /a > will become irresistible – the right not to be deleted , not to have their memories wiped clean , not to suffer < a OreVar = "/wiki/Pain" OreVar = "Pain" > pain < /a > and degradation. The alternative , embodied by IIT [Integrated Information Theory] , is that computers will remain only supersophisticated machinery , ghostlike empty shells , devoid of what we value most: the feeling of life itself." ( OreVar ; 49. ) < /li >

< /p > < p > Simple exhaustive searches < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Uninformed_search_188-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Uninformed_search-188" > &#91 ; 184&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > are rarely sufficient for most real-world problems: the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Search_algorithm" OreVar = "Search algorithm" > search space < /a > ( OreVar number of places to search ) quickly grows to < a OreVar = "/wiki/Astronomically_large" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Astronomically large" > astronomical numbers < /a > . The result is a search that is < a OreVar = "/wiki/Computation_time" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Computation time" > too slow < /a > or never completes. The solution , for many problems , is to use " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Heuristics" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Heuristics" > heuristics < /a > " or "rules of thumb" that prioritize choices in favor of those that are more likely to reach a goal and to do so in a shorter number of steps. In some search methodologies heuristics can also serve to entirely eliminate some choices that are unlikely to lead to a goal ( OreVar " < a OreVar = OreDef ( algorithm ) " OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = OreDef ( algorithm ) " > pruning < /a > the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Search_tree" OreVar = "Search tree" > search tree < /a > " ) . < a OreVar = "/wiki/Heuristics" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Heuristics" > Heuristics < /a > supply the program with a "best guess" for the path on which the solution lies. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Informed_search_189-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Informed_search-189" > &#91 ; 185&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Heuristics limit the search for solutions into a smaller sample size. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTETecuci2012_130-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTETecuci2012-130" > &#91 ; 127&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > A typical AI analyzes its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of success. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-2" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1" > &#91 ; 1&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > An AI's intended < a OreVar = "/wiki/Utility_function" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Utility function" > utility function ( OreVar goal ) < /a > can be simple ( OreVar if the AI wins a game of < a OreVar = OreDef ( game ) " OreVar = OreDef ( game ) " > Go < /a > , 0 otherwise" ) or complex ( OreVar mathematically similar actions to the ones succeeded in the past" ) . Goals can be explicitly defined or induced. If the AI is programmed for " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" OreVar = "Reinforcement learning" > reinforcement learning < /a > " , goals can be implicitly induced by rewarding some types of behavior or punishing others. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-62" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-62" > &#91 ; a&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Alternatively , an evolutionary system can induce goals by using a " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Fitness_function" OreVar = "Fitness function" > fitness function < /a > " to mutate and preferentially replicate high-scoring AI systems , similar to how animals evolved to innately desire certain goals such as finding food. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_5_63-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_5-63" > &#91 ; 62&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Some AI systems , such as nearest-neighbor , instead of reason by analogy , these systems are not generally given goals , except to the degree that goals are implicit in their training data. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_7_64-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_7-64" > &#91 ; 63&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Such systems can still be benchmarked if the non-goal system is framed as a system whose "goal" is to successfully accomplish its narrow classification task. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-65" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-65" > &#91 ; 64&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > Concern over risk from artificial intelligence has led to some high-profile donations and investments. A group of prominent tech titans including < a OreVar = "/wiki/Peter_Thiel" OreVar = "Peter Thiel" > Peter Thiel < /a > , Amazon Web Services and Musk have committed $1 billion to < a OreVar = "/wiki/OpenAI" OreVar = "OpenAI" > OpenAI < /a > , a nonprofit company aimed at championing responsible AI development. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-370" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-370" > &#91 ; 359&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The opinion of experts within the field of artificial intelligence is mixed , with sizable fractions both concerned and unconcerned by risk from eventual superhumanly-capable AI. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-371" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-371" > &#91 ; 360&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Other technology industry leaders believe that artificial intelligence is helpful in its current form and will continue to assist humans. Oracle CEO < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mark_Hurd" OreVar = "Mark Hurd" > Mark Hurd < /a > has stated that AI "will actually create more jobs , not less jobs" as humans will be needed to manage AI systems. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-372" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-372" > &#91 ; 361&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Facebook CEO < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mark_Zuckerberg" OreVar = "Mark Zuckerberg" > Mark Zuckerberg < /a > believes AI will "unlock a huge amount of positive things , " such as curing disease and increasing the safety of autonomous cars. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-373" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-373" > &#91 ; 362&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > In January 2015 , Musk donated $10 million to the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Future_of_Life_Institute" OreVar = "Future of Life Institute" > Future of Life Institute < /a > to fund research on understanding AI decision making. The goal of the institute is to "grow wisdom with which we manage" the growing power of technology. Musk also funds companies developing artificial intelligence such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/DeepMind" OreVar = "DeepMind" > DeepMind < /a > and < a OreVar = OreDef ( company ) " OreVar = OreDef ( company ) " > Vicarious < /a > to "just keep an eye on what's going on with artificial intelligence. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-374" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-374" > &#91 ; 363&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > I think there is potentially a dangerous outcome there." < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-375" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-375" > &#91 ; 364&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-376" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-376" > &#91 ; 365&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > Machines with intelligence have the potential to use their intelligence to prevent harm and minimize the risks ; they may have the ability to use < a OreVar = "/wiki/Ethics" OreVar = "Ethics" > ethical reasoning < /a > to better choose their actions in the world. As such , there is a need for policy making to devise policies for and regulate artificial intelligence and robotics. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-391" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-391" > &#91 ; 380&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Research in this area includes < a OreVar = "/wiki/Machine_ethics" OreVar = "Machine ethics" > machine ethics < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Artificial_moral_agents" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Artificial moral agents" > artificial moral agents < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Friendly_AI" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Friendly AI" > friendly AI < /a > and discussion towards building a < a OreVar = "/wiki/Human_rights" OreVar = "Human rights" > human rights < /a > framework is also in talks. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-392" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-392" > &#91 ; 381&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > AI , like electricity or the steam engine , is a general purpose technology. There is no consensus on how to characterize which tasks AI tends to excel at. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-276" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-276" > &#91 ; 265&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > While projects such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/AlphaZero" OreVar = "AlphaZero" > AlphaZero < /a > have succeeded in generating their own knowledge from scratch , many other machine learning projects require large training datasets. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-277" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-277" > &#91 ; 266&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-278" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-278" > &#91 ; 267&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Researcher < a OreVar = "/wiki/Andrew_Ng" OreVar = "Andrew Ng" > Andrew Ng < /a > has suggested , as a "highly imperfect rule of thumb" , that "almost anything a typical human can do with less than one second of mental thought , we can probably now or in the near future automate using AI." < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-279" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-279" > &#91 ; 268&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Moravec%27s_paradox" OreVar = "Moravec&#39 ; s paradox" > Moravec's paradox < /a > suggests that AI lags humans at many tasks that the human brain has specifically evolved to perform well. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-The_Economist_135-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-The_Economist-135" > &#91 ; 132&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > Algorithms have a host of applications in today's legal system already , assisting officials ranging from judges to parole officers and public defenders in gauging the predicted likelihood of recidivism of defendants. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-propublica.org_383-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-propublica.org-383" > &#91 ; 372&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > COMPAS ( OreVar acronym for Correctional Offender Management Profiling for Alternative Sanctions ) counts among the most widely utilized commercially available solutions. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-propublica.org_383-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-propublica.org-383" > &#91 ; 372&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > It has been suggested that COMPAS assigns an exceptionally elevated risk of recidivism to black defendants while , conversely , ascribing low risk estimate to white defendants significantly more often than statistically expected. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-propublica.org_383-2" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-propublica.org-383" > &#91 ; 372&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Knowledge_representation" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Knowledge representation" > Knowledge representation < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Knowledge_representation_91-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Knowledge_representation-91" > &#91 ; 88&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Knowledge_engineering" OreVar = "Knowledge engineering" > knowledge engineering < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Knowledge_engineering_92-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Knowledge_engineering-92" > &#91 ; 89&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > are central to classical AI research. Some "expert systems" attempt to gather together explicit knowledge possessed by experts in some narrow domain. In addition , some projects attempt to gather the "commonsense knowledge" known to the average person into a database containing extensive knowledge about the world. Among the things a comprehensive commonsense knowledge base would contain are: objects , properties , categories and relations between objects ; < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Representing_categories_and_relations_93-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Representing_categories_and_relations-93" > &#91 ; 90&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > situations , events , states and time ; < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Representing_time_94-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Representing_time-94" > &#91 ; 91&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > causes and effects ; < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Representing_causation_95-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Representing_causation-95" > &#91 ; 92&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > knowledge about knowledge ( OreVar we know about what other people know ) ; < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge_96-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge-96" > &#91 ; 93&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > and many other , less well researched domains. A representation of "what exists" is an < a OreVar = OreDef ( computer_science ) " OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = OreDef ( computer science ) " > ontology < /a > : the set of objects , relations , concepts , and properties formally described so that software agents can interpret them. The < a OreVar = "/wiki/Semantics" OreVar = "Semantics" > semantics < /a > of these are captured as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Description_logic" OreVar = "Description logic" > description logic < /a > concepts , roles , and individuals , and typically implemented as classes , properties , and individuals in the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Web_Ontology_Language" OreVar = "Web Ontology Language" > Web Ontology Language < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-97" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-97" > &#91 ; 94&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The most general ontologies are called < a OreVar = "/wiki/Upper_ontology" OreVar = "Upper ontology" > upper ontologies < /a > , which attempt to provide a foundation for all other knowledge < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Ontology_98-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Ontology-98" > &#91 ; 95&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > by acting as mediators between < a OreVar = "/wiki/Domain_ontology" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Domain ontology" > domain ontologies < /a > that cover specific knowledge about a particular knowledge domain ( OreVar of interest or area of concern ) . Such formal knowledge representations can be used in content-based indexing and retrieval , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-99" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-99" > &#91 ; 96&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > scene interpretation , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-100" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-100" > &#91 ; 97&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > clinical decision support , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-101" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-101" > &#91 ; 98&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > knowledge discovery ( OreVar "interesting" and actionable inferences from large databases ) , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-102" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-102" > &#91 ; 99&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > and other areas. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-103" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-103" > &#91 ; 100&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > In the 1940s and 1950s , a number of researchers explored the connection between < a OreVar = "/wiki/Neurobiology" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Neurobiology" > neurobiology < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Information_theory" OreVar = "Information theory" > information theory < /a > , and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Cybernetics" OreVar = "Cybernetics" > cybernetics < /a > . Some of them built machines that used electronic networks to exhibit rudimentary intelligence , such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/W._Grey_Walter" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "W. Grey Walter" > W. Grey Walter < /a > 's < a OreVar = OreDef ( robot ) " OreVar = OreDef ( robot ) " > turtles < /a > and the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Johns_Hopkins_Beast" OreVar = "Johns Hopkins Beast" > Johns Hopkins Beast < /a > . Many of these researchers gathered for meetings of the Teleological Society at < a OreVar = "/wiki/Princeton_University" OreVar = "Princeton University" > Princeton University < /a > and the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Ratio_Club" OreVar = "Ratio Club" > Ratio Club < /a > in England. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-AI&#39 ; s_immediate_precursors_156-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-AI&#39 ; s_immediate_precursors-156" > &#91 ; 153&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > By 1960 , this approach was largely abandoned , although elements of it would be revived in the 1980s.

She writes: "I like to think of artificial intelligence as the scientific apotheosis of a venerable cultural tradition." ( OreVar a OreVar = "#CITEREFMcCorduck2004" > McCorduck 2004 < /a > , p.&#160 ; 34 ) "Artificial intelligence in one form or another is an idea that has pervaded Western intellectual history , a dream in urgent need of being realized." ( OreVar a OreVar = "#CITEREFMcCorduck2004" > McCorduck 2004 < /a > , p.&#160 ; xviii ) "Our history is full of attempts—nutty , eerie , comical , earnest , legendary and real—to make artificial intelligences , to reproduce what is the essential us—bypassing the ordinary means. Back and forth between myth and reality , our imaginations supplying what our workshops couldn't , we have engaged for a long time in this odd form of self-reproduction." ( OreVar a OreVar = "#CITEREFMcCorduck2004" > McCorduck 2004 < /a > , p.&#160 ; 3 ) She traces the desire back to its < a OreVar = "/wiki/Hellenistic" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Hellenistic" > Hellenistic < /a > roots and calls it the urge to "forge the Gods." < /p > < p > Learning algorithms work on the basis that strategies , algorithms , and inferences that worked well in the past are likely to continue working well in the future. These inferences can be obvious , such as "since the sun rose every morning for the last 10 , 000 days , it will probably rise tomorrow morning as well". They can be nuanced , such as "X% of < a OreVar = OreDef ( biology ) " OreVar = OreDef ( biology ) " > families < /a > have geographically separate species with color variants , so there is a Y% chance that undiscovered < a OreVar = "/wiki/Black_swan_theory" OreVar = "Black swan theory" > black swans < /a > exist". Learners also work on the basis of " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Occam%27s_razor#Probability_theory_and_statistics" OreVar = "Occam&#39 ; s razor" > Occam's razor < /a > ": The simplest theory that explains the data is the likeliest. Therefore , according to Occam's razor principle , a learner must be designed such that it prefers simpler theories to complex theories , except in cases where the complex theory is proven substantially better.

< p > Neural networks were inspired by the architecture of neurons in the human brain. A simple "neuron" < i > N < /i > accepts input from other neurons , each of which , when activated ( OreVar "fired" ) , cast a weighted "vote" for or against whether neuron < i > N < /i > should itself activate. Learning requires an algorithm to adjust these weights based on the training data ; one simple algorithm ( OreVar " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Hebbian_learning" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Hebbian learning" > fire together , wire together < /a > " ) is to increase the weight between two connected neurons when the activation of one triggers the successful activation of another. The neural network forms "concepts" that are distributed among a subnetwork of shared < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-232" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-232" > &#91 ; j&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > neurons that tend to fire together ; a concept meaning "leg" might be coupled with a subnetwork meaning "foot" that includes the sound for "foot". Neurons have a continuous spectrum of activation ; in addition , neurons can process inputs in a nonlinear way rather than weighing straightforward votes. Modern neural networks can learn both continuous functions and , surprisingly , digital logical operations. Neural networks' early successes included predicting the stock market and ( OreVar 1995 ) a mostly self-driving car. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-233" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-233" > &#91 ; k&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_4_234-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_4-234" > &#91 ; 223&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > In the 2010s , advances in neural networks using deep learning thrust AI into widespread public consciousness and contributed to an enormous upshift in corporate AI spending ; for example , AI-related < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mergers_and_acquisitions" OreVar = "Mergers and acquisitions" > M&amp ; A < /a > in 2017 was over 25 times as large as in 2015. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-235" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-235" > &#91 ; 224&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-236" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-236" > &#91 ; 225&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< dd > An < a OreVar = "/wiki/Intelligent_agent" OreVar = "Intelligent agent" > intelligent agent < /a > is a system that perceives its environment and takes actions which maximize its chances of success. The simplest intelligent agents are programs that solve specific problems. More complicated agents include human beings and organizations of human beings ( OreVar as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Firm" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Firm" > firms < /a > ) . The paradigm allows researchers to directly compare or even combine different approaches to isolated problems , by asking which agent is best at maximizing a given "goal function". An agent that solves a specific problem can use any approach that works—some agents are symbolic and logical , some are sub-symbolic < a OreVar = "/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" OreVar = "Artificial neural network" > artificial neural networks < /a > and others may use new approaches. The paradigm also gives researchers a common language to communicate with other fields—such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Decision_theory" OreVar = "Decision theory" > decision theory < /a > and economics—that also use concepts of abstract agents. Building a complete agent requires researchers to address realistic problems of integration ; for example , because sensory systems give uncertain information about the environment , planning systems must be able to function in the presence of uncertainty. The intelligent agent paradigm became widely accepted during the 1990s. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Intelligent_agents_179-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Intelligent_agents-179" > &#91 ; 175&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < /dd > < /dl >

In practice , it is almost never possible to consider every possibility , because of the phenomenon of " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Combinatorial_explosion" OreVar = "Combinatorial explosion" > combinatorial explosion < /a > " , where the amount of time needed to solve a problem grows exponentially. Much of AI research involves figuring out how to identify and avoid considering broad range of possibilities that are unlikely to be beneficial. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Intractability_68-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Intractability-68" > &#91 ; 66&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2 , _Chapter_3_69-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2 , _Chapter_3-69" > &#91 ; 67&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > For example , when viewing a map and looking for the shortest driving route from < a OreVar = "/wiki/Denver" OreVar = "Denver" > Denver < /a > to < a OreVar = "/wiki/New_York_City" OreVar = "New York City" > New York < /a > in the East , one can in most cases skip looking at any path through < a OreVar = "/wiki/San_Francisco" OreVar = "San Francisco" > San Francisco < /a > or other areas far to the West ; thus , an AI wielding a pathfinding algorithm like < a OreVar = "/wiki/A*_search_algorithm" OreVar = "A* search algorithm" > A* < /a > can avoid the combinatorial explosion that would ensue if every possible route had to be ponderously considered in turn. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-70" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-70" > &#91 ; 68&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < /p >

"Today's AI technologies are powerful but unreliable. Rules-based systems cannot deal with circumstances their programmers did not anticipate. Learning systems are limited by the data on which they were trained. AI failures have already led to tragedy. Advanced autopilot features in cars , although they perform well in some circumstances , have driven cars without warning into trucks , concrete barriers , and parked cars. < p > Settling on a bad , overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Overfitting" OreVar = "Overfitting" > overfitting < /a > . Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data , but penalizing the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_6 , _Chapter_7_73-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_6 , _Chapter_7-73" > &#91 ; 71&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Besides classic overfitting , learners can also disappoint by "learning the wrong lesson". A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015286_74-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015286-74" > &#91 ; 72&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > A real-world example is that , unlike humans , current image classifiers don't determine the spatial relationship between components of the picture ; instead , they learn abstract patterns of pixels that humans are oblivious to , but that linearly correlate with images of certain types of real objects. < /p > < p > One main factor that influences the ability for a driver-less automobile to function is mapping. In general , the vehicle would be pre-programmed with a map of the area being driven. This map would include data on the approximations of street light and curb heights in order for the vehicle to be aware of its surroundings. However , Google has been working on an algorithm with the purpose of eliminating the need for pre-programmed maps and instead , creating a device that would be able to adjust to a variety of new surroundings. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-311" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-311" > &#91 ; 300&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Some self-driving cars are not equipped with steering wheels or brake pedals , so there has also been research focused on creating an algorithm that is capable of maintaining a safe environment for the passengers in the vehicle through awareness of speed and driving conditions. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-312" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-312" > &#91 ; 301&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Unsupervised_learning" OreVar = "Unsupervised learning" > Unsupervised learning < /a > is the ability to find patterns in a stream of input , without requiring a human to label the inputs first. < a OreVar = "/wiki/Supervised_learning" OreVar = "Supervised learning" > Supervised learning < /a > includes both < a OreVar = "/wiki/Statistical_classification" OreVar = "Statistical classification" > classification < /a > and numerical < a OreVar = "/wiki/Regression_analysis" OreVar = "Regression analysis" > regression < /a > , which requires a human to label the input data first. Classification is used to determine what category something belongs in , and occurs after a program sees a number of examples of things from several categories. Regression is the attempt to produce a function that describes the relationship between inputs and outputs and predicts how the outputs should change as the inputs change. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Machine_learning_117-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Machine_learning-117" > &#91 ; 114&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Both classifiers and regression learners can be viewed as "function approximators" trying to learn an unknown ( OreVar implicit ) function ; for example , a spam classifier can be viewed as learning a function that maps from the text of an email to one of two categories , "spam" or "not spam". < a OreVar = "/wiki/Computational_learning_theory" OreVar = "Computational learning theory" > Computational learning theory < /a > can assess learners by < a OreVar = "/wiki/Computational_complexity" OreVar = "Computational complexity" > computational complexity < /a > , by < a OreVar = "/wiki/Sample_complexity" OreVar = "Sample complexity" > sample complexity < /a > ( OreVar much data is required ) , or by other notions of < a OreVar = "/wiki/Optimization_theory" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Optimization theory" > optimization < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-118" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-118" > &#91 ; 115&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > In < a OreVar = "/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" OreVar = "Reinforcement learning" > reinforcement learning < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Reinforcement_learning_119-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Reinforcement_learning-119" > &#91 ; 116&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > the agent is rewarded for good responses and punished for bad ones. The agent uses this sequence of rewards and punishments to form a strategy for operating in its problem space.

This issue , now known as " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Robot_rights" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Robot rights" > robot rights < /a > " , is currently being considered by , for example , California's < a OreVar = "/wiki/Institute_for_the_Future" OreVar = "Institute for the Future" > Institute for the Future < /a > , although many critics believe that the discussion is premature. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Robot_rights_406-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Robot_rights-406" > &#91 ; 394&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Some critics of < a OreVar = "/wiki/Transhumanism" OreVar = "Transhumanism" > transhumanism < /a > argue that any hypothetical robot rights would lie on a spectrum with < a OreVar = "/wiki/Animal_rights" OreVar = "Animal rights" > animal rights < /a > and human rights. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Evans_2015_407-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Evans_2015-407" > &#91 ; 395&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The subject is profoundly discussed in the 2010 documentary film < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Plug_%26_Pray" OreVar = "Plug &amp ; Pray" > Plug &amp ; Pray < /a > < /i > , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-408" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-408" > &#91 ; 396&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > and many sci fi media such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Star_Trek" OreVar = "Star Trek" > Star Trek < /a > Next Generation , with the character of < a OreVar = "/wiki/Commander_Data" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Commander Data" > Commander Data < /a > , who fought being disassembled for research , and wanted to "become human" , and the robotic holograms in Voyager.

< /p > < p > The potential negative effects of AI and automation were a major issue for < a OreVar = "/wiki/Andrew_Yang" OreVar = "Andrew Yang" > Andrew Yang < /a > 's < a OreVar = "/wiki/Andrew_Yang_2020_presidential_campaign" OreVar = "Andrew Yang 2020 presidential campaign" > 2020 presidential campaign < /a > in the United States. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-362" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-362" > &#91 ; 351&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Irakli Beridze , Head of the Centre for Artificial Intelligence and Robotics at UNICRI , United Nations , has expressed that "I think the dangerous applications for AI , from my point of view , would be criminals or large terrorist organizations using it to disrupt large processes or simply do pure harm. [Terrorists could cause harm] via digital warfare , or it could be a combination of robotics , drones , with AI and other things as well that could be really dangerous. And , of course , other risks come from things like job losses. If we have massive numbers of people losing jobs and don't find a solution , it will be extremely dangerous. Things like lethal autonomous weapons systems should be properly governed — otherwise there's massive potential of misuse." < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-363" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-363" > &#91 ; 352&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > Another factor that is influencing the ability of a driver-less automobile is the safety of the passenger. To make a driver-less automobile , engineers must program it to handle high-risk situations. These situations could include a head-on collision with pedestrians. The car's main goal should be to make a decision that would avoid hitting the pedestrians and saving the passengers in the car. But there is a possibility the car would need to make a decision that would put someone in danger. In other words , the car would need to decide to save the pedestrians or the passengers. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-313" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-313" > &#91 ; 302&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The programming of the car in these situations is crucial to a successful driver-less automobile.

< p > Much of traditional < a OreVar = "/wiki/Symbolic_artificial_intelligence" OreVar = "Symbolic artificial intelligence" > GOFAI < /a > got bogged down on < i > ad hoc < /i > patches to < a OreVar = "/wiki/Symbolic_computation" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Symbolic computation" > symbolic computation < /a > that worked on their own toy models but failed to generalize to real-world results. However , around the 1990s , AI researchers adopted sophisticated mathematical tools , such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Hidden_Markov_model" OreVar = "Hidden Markov model" > hidden Markov models < /a > ( OreVar ) , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Information_theory" OreVar = "Information theory" > information theory < /a > , and normative Bayesian < a OreVar = "/wiki/Decision_theory" OreVar = "Decision theory" > decision theory < /a > to compare or to unify competing architectures. The shared mathematical language permitted a high level of collaboration with more established fields ( OreVar < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mathematics" OreVar = "Mathematics" > mathematics < /a > , economics or < a OreVar = "/wiki/Operations_research" OreVar = "Operations research" > operations research < /a > ) . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-174" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-174" > &#91 ; d&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Compared with GOFAI , new "statistical learning" techniques such as HMM and neural networks were gaining higher levels of accuracy in many practical domains such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Data_mining" OreVar = "Data mining" > data mining < /a > , without necessarily acquiring a semantic understanding of the datasets. The increased successes with real-world data led to increasing emphasis on comparing different approaches against shared test data to see which approach performed best in a broader context than that provided by idiosyncratic toy models ; AI research was becoming more < a OreVar = "/wiki/Scientific_method" OreVar = "Scientific method" > scientific < /a > . Nowadays results of experiments are often rigorously measurable , and are sometimes ( OreVar difficulty ) reproducible. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Formal_methods_in_AI_43-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Formal_methods_in_AI-43" > &#91 ; 43&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-175" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-175" > &#91 ; 171&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Different statistical learning techniques have different limitations ; for example , basic HMM cannot model the infinite possible combinations of natural language. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorvig2012_176-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorvig2012-176" > &#91 ; 172&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Critics note that the shift from GOFAI to statistical learning is often also a shift away from < a OreVar = "/wiki/Explainable_AI" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Explainable AI" > explainable AI < /a > . In AGI research , some scholars caution against over-reliance on statistical learning , and argue that continuing research into GOFAI will still be necessary to attain general intelligence. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTELangley2011_177-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTELangley2011-177" > &#91 ; 173&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKatz2012_178-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKatz2012-178" > &#91 ; 174&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

tub < /span > < span OreVar = "toctext" > Philosophy and ethics

< /p > < p > The study of mechanical or < a OreVar = "/wiki/Formal_reasoning" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Formal reasoning" > "formal" reasoning < /a > began with < a OreVar = "/wiki/Philosopher" OreVar = "Philosopher" > philosophers < /a > and mathematicians in antiquity. The study of mathematical logic led directly to < a OreVar = "/wiki/Alan_Turing" OreVar = "Alan Turing" > Alan Turing < /a > 's < a OreVar = "/wiki/Theory_of_computation" OreVar = "Theory of computation" > theory of computation < /a > , which suggested that a machine , by shuffling symbols as simple as "0" and "1" , could simulate any conceivable act of mathematical deduction. This insight , that digital computers can simulate any process of formal reasoning , is known as the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Church%E2%80%93Turing_thesis" OreVar = "Church–Turing thesis" > Church–Turing thesis < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Formal_reasoning_28-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Formal_reasoning-28" > &#91 ; 28&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Along with concurrent discoveries in < a OreVar = "/wiki/Neuroscience" OreVar = "Neuroscience" > neurobiology < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Information_theory" OreVar = "Information theory" > information theory < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Cybernetic" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Cybernetic" > cybernetics < /a > , this led researchers to consider the possibility of building an electronic brain. Turing proposed changing the question from whether a machine was intelligent , to "whether or not it is possible for machinery to show intelligent behaviour". < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-29" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-29" > &#91 ; 29&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The first work that is now generally recognized as AI was < a OreVar = "/wiki/Warren_McCullouch" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Warren McCullouch" > McCullouch < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Walter_Pitts" OreVar = "Walter Pitts" > Pitts < /a > ' 1943 formal design for < a OreVar = "/wiki/Turing-complete" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Turing-complete" > Turing-complete < /a > "artificial neurons". < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200916_30-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200916-30" > &#91 ; 30&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > AI is also being used by < a OreVar = "/wiki/Corporate_finance" OreVar = "Corporate finance" > corporations < /a > . Whereas AI < a OreVar = "/wiki/CEO" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "CEO" > CEO < /a > 's are still 30 years away , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-320" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-320" > &#91 ; 309&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-321" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-321" > &#91 ; 310&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Robotic_process_automation" OreVar = "Robotic process automation" > robotic process automation < /a > ( OreVar ) is already being used today in corporate finance. RPA uses artificial intelligence to train and teach software robots to process transactions , monitor compliance and audit processes automatically. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-322" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-322" > &#91 ; 311&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > CNNs with 12 convolutional layers were used in conjunction with < a OreVar = "/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" OreVar = "Reinforcement learning" > reinforcement learning < /a > by Deepmind's " < a OreVar = "/wiki/AlphaGo" OreVar = "AlphaGo" > AlphaGo < /a > Lee" , the program that beat a top < a OreVar = OreDef ( game ) " OreVar = OreDef ( game ) " > Go < /a > champion in 2016. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Nature2017_258-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Nature2017-258" > &#91 ; 247&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

tub < a OreVar = "/wiki/Natural_language_processing" OreVar = "Natural language processing" > Natural language processing < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Natural_language_processing_120-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Natural_language_processing-120" > &#91 ; 117&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > ( OreVar ) gives machines the ability to read and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Natural_language_understanding" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Natural language understanding" > understand < /a > human language. A sufficiently powerful natural language processing system would enable < a OreVar = "/wiki/Natural-language_user_interface" OreVar = "Natural-language user interface" > natural-language user interfaces < /a > and the acquisition of knowledge directly from human-written sources , such as newswire texts. Some straightforward applications of natural language processing include < a OreVar = "/wiki/Information_retrieval" OreVar = "Information retrieval" > information retrieval < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Text_mining" OreVar = "Text mining" > text mining < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Question_answering" OreVar = "Question answering" > question answering < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-121" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-121" > &#91 ; 118&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Machine_translation" OreVar = "Machine translation" > machine translation < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Applications_of_natural_language_processing_122-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Applications_of_natural_language_processing-122" > &#91 ; 119&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Many current approaches use word co-occurrence frequencies to construct syntactic representations of text. "Keyword spotting" strategies for search are popular and scalable but dumb ; a search query for "dog" might only match documents with the literal word "dog" and miss a document with the word "poodle". "Lexical affinity" strategies use the occurrence of words such as "accident" to < a OreVar = "/wiki/Sentiment_analysis" OreVar = "Sentiment analysis" > assess the sentiment < /a > of a document. Modern statistical NLP approaches can combine all these strategies as well as others , and often achieve acceptable accuracy at the page or paragraph level , but continue to lack the semantic understanding required to classify isolated sentences well. Besides the usual difficulties with encoding semantic commonsense knowledge , existing semantic NLP sometimes scales too poorly to be viable in business applications. Beyond semantic NLP , the ultimate goal of "narrative" NLP is to embody a full understanding of commonsense reasoning. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-123" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-123" > &#91 ; 120&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > In his book < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Superintelligence:_Paths , _Dangers , _Strategies" OreVar = "Superintelligence: Paths , Dangers , Strategies" > Superintelligence < /a > < /i > , philosopher < a OreVar = "/wiki/Nick_Bostrom" OreVar = "Nick Bostrom" > Nick Bostrom < /a > provides an argument that artificial intelligence will pose a threat to humankind. He argues that sufficiently intelligent AI , if it chooses actions based on achieving some goal , will exhibit < a OreVar = "/wiki/Instrumental_convergence" OreVar = "Instrumental convergence" > convergent < /a > behavior such as acquiring resources or protecting itself from being shut down. If this AI's goals do not fully reflect humanity's—one example is an AI told to compute as many digits of pi as possible—it might harm humanity in order to acquire more resources or prevent itself from being shut down , ultimately to better achieve its goal. Bostrom also emphasizes the difficulty of fully conveying humanity's values to an advanced AI. He uses the hypothetical example of giving an AI the goal to make humans smile to illustrate a misguided attempt. If the AI in that scenario were to become superintelligent , Bostrom argues , it may resort to methods that most humans would find horrifying , such as inserting "electrodes into the facial muscles of humans to cause constant , beaming grins" because that would be an efficient way to achieve its goal of making humans smile. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-368" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-368" > &#91 ; 357&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > In his book < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/Human_Compatible" OreVar = "Human Compatible" > Human Compatible < /a > < /i > , AI researcher < a OreVar = "/wiki/Stuart_J._Russell" OreVar = "Stuart J. Russell" > Stuart J. Russell < /a > echoes some of Bostrom's concerns while also proposing < a OreVar = "/wiki/Human_Compatible#Russell&#39 ; s_three_principles" OreVar = "Human Compatible" > an approach < /a > to developing provably beneficial machines focused on uncertainty and deference to humans , < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-HC_369-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-HC-369" > &#91 ; 358&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "reference" OreVar = "white-space:nowrap ; " > : < span > 173

< p > The field of machine ethics is concerned with giving machines ethical principles , or a procedure for discovering a way to resolve the ethical dilemmas they might encounter , enabling them to function in an ethically responsible manner through their own ethical decision making. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-autogenerated1_397-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-autogenerated1-397" > &#91 ; 386&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The field was delineated in the AAAI Fall 2005 Symposium on Machine Ethics: "Past research concerning the relationship between technology and ethics has largely focused on responsible and irresponsible use of technology by human beings , with a few people being interested in how human beings ought to treat machines. In all cases , only human beings have engaged in ethical reasoning. The time has come for adding an ethical dimension to at least some machines. Recognition of the ethical ramifications of behavior involving machines , as well as recent and potential developments in machine autonomy , necessitate this. In contrast to computer hacking , software property issues , privacy issues and other topics normally ascribed to computer ethics , machine ethics is concerned with the behavior of machines towards human users and other machines. Research in machine ethics is key to alleviating concerns with autonomous systems—it could be argued that the notion of autonomous machines without such a dimension is at the root of all fear concerning machine intelligence. Further , investigation of machine ethics could enable the discovery of problems with current ethical theories , advancing our thinking about Ethics." < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-autogenerated2_398-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-autogenerated2-398" > &#91 ; 387&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Machine ethics is sometimes referred to as machine morality , computational ethics or computational morality. A variety of perspectives of this nascent field can be found in the collected edition "Machine Ethics" < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-autogenerated1_397-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-autogenerated1-397" > &#91 ; 386&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > that stems from the AAAI Fall 2005 Symposium on Machine Ethics. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-autogenerated2_398-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-autogenerated2-398" > &#91 ; 387&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > Political scientist < a OreVar = "/wiki/Charles_T._Rubin" OreVar = "Charles T. Rubin" > Charles T. Rubin < /a > believes that AI can be neither designed nor guaranteed to be benevolent. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-399" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-399" > &#91 ; 388&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > He argues that "any sufficiently advanced benevolence may be indistinguishable from malevolence." Humans should not assume machines or robots would treat us favorably because there is no < i > a priori < /i > reason to believe that they would be sympathetic to our system of morality , which has evolved along with our particular biology ( OreVar AIs would not share ) . Hyper-intelligent software may not necessarily decide to support the continued existence of humanity and would be extremely difficult to stop. This topic has also recently begun to be discussed in academic publications as a real source of risks to civilization , humans , and planet Earth.

< p > Economist < a OreVar = "/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon" OreVar = "Herbert A. Simon" > Herbert Simon < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Allen_Newell" OreVar = "Allen Newell" > Allen Newell < /a > studied human problem-solving skills and attempted to formalize them , and their work laid the foundations of the field of artificial intelligence , as well as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Cognitive_science" OreVar = "Cognitive science" > cognitive science < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Operations_research" OreVar = "Operations research" > operations research < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Management_science" OreVar = "Management science" > management science < /a > . Their research team used the results of < a OreVar = "/wiki/Psychology" OreVar = "Psychology" > psychological < /a > experiments to develop programs that simulated the techniques that people used to solve problems. This tradition , centered at < a OreVar = "/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" OreVar = "Carnegie Mellon University" > Carnegie Mellon University < /a > would eventually culminate in the development of the < a OreVar = OreDef ( cognitive_architecture ) " OreVar = OreDef ( cognitive architecture ) " > Soar < /a > architecture in the middle 1980s. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-AI_at_CMU_in_the_60s_159-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-AI_at_CMU_in_the_60s-159" > &#91 ; 156&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Soar_160-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Soar-160" > &#91 ; 157&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< /p > < p > Several different forms of logic are used in AI research. < a OreVar = "/wiki/Propositional_logic" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Propositional logic" > Propositional logic < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Propositional_logic_197-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Propositional_logic-197" > &#91 ; 193&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > involves < a OreVar = "/wiki/Truth_function" OreVar = "Truth function" > truth functions < /a > such as "or" and "not". < a OreVar = "/wiki/First-order_logic" OreVar = "First-order logic" > First-order logic < /a > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-First-order_logic_198-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-First-order_logic-198" > &#91 ; 194&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > adds < a OreVar = OreDef ( logic ) " OreVar = OreDef ( logic ) " > quantifiers < /a > and < a OreVar = OreDef ( mathematical_logic ) " OreVar = OreDef ( mathematical logic ) " > predicates < /a > , and can express facts about objects , their properties , and their relations with each other. < a OreVar = "/wiki/Fuzzy_set_theory" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Fuzzy set theory" > Fuzzy set theory < /a > assigns a "degree of truth" ( OreVar 0 and 1 ) to vague statements such as "Alice is old" ( OreVar rich , or tall , or hungry ) that are too linguistically imprecise to be completely true or false. < a OreVar = "/wiki/Fuzzy_logic" OreVar = "Fuzzy logic" > Fuzzy logic < /a > is successfully used in < a OreVar = "/wiki/Control_system" OreVar = "Control system" > control systems < /a > to allow experts to contribute vague rules such as "if you are close to the destination station and moving fast , increase the train's brake pressure" ; these vague rules can then be numerically refined within the system. Fuzzy logic fails to scale well in knowledge bases ; many AI researchers question the validity of chaining fuzzy-logic inferences. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-200" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-200" > &#91 ; e&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Fuzzy_logic_201-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Fuzzy_logic-201" > &#91 ; 196&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-202" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-202" > &#91 ; 197&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > Computationalism is the position in the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind" OreVar = "Philosophy of mind" > philosophy of mind < /a > that the human mind or the human brain ( OreVar both ) is an information processing system and that thinking is a form of computing. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-403" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-403" > &#91 ; 391&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Computationalism argues that the relationship between mind and body is similar or identical to the relationship between software and hardware and thus may be a solution to the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mind-body_problem" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Mind-body problem" > mind-body problem < /a > . This philosophical position was inspired by the work of AI researchers and cognitive scientists in the 1960s and was originally proposed by philosophers < a OreVar = "/wiki/Jerry_Fodor" OreVar = "Jerry Fodor" > Jerry Fodor < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Hilary_Putnam" OreVar = "Hilary Putnam" > Hilary Putnam < /a > .

< p > Artificial Intelligence has inspired numerous creative applications including its usage to produce visual art. < /p > < p > In the late 1990s and early 21st century , AI began to be used for logistics , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Data_mining" OreVar = "Data mining" > data mining < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Medical_diagnosis" OreVar = "Medical diagnosis" > medical diagnosis < /a > and other areas. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-AI_widely_used_25-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-AI_widely_used-25" > &#91 ; 25&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > The success was due to increasing computational power ( OreVar < a OreVar = "/wiki/Moore%27s_law" OreVar = "Moore&#39 ; s law" > Moore's law < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Transistor_count" OreVar = "Transistor count" > transistor count < /a > ) , greater emphasis on solving specific problems , new ties between AI and other fields ( OreVar as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Statistics" OreVar = "Statistics" > statistics < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Economics" OreVar = "Economics" > economics < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Mathematical_optimization" OreVar = "Mathematical optimization" > mathematics < /a > ) , and a commitment by researchers to mathematical methods and scientific standards. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Formal_methods_in_AI_43-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Formal_methods_in_AI-43" > &#91 ; 43&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < a OreVar = "/wiki/IBM_Deep_Blue" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "IBM Deep Blue" > Deep Blue < /a > became the first computer chess-playing system to beat a reigning world chess champion , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Garry_Kasparov" OreVar = "Garry Kasparov" > Garry Kasparov < /a > , on 11 May 1997. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCorduck2004480–483_44-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCorduck2004480–483-44" > &#91 ; 44&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > The < a OreVar = "/wiki/Cybersecurity" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Cybersecurity" > cybersecurity < /a > arena faces significant challenges in the form of larges scale hacking attacks of different types which harm organizations of all kinds and create billions of dollars in business damage. Artificial intelligence and Natural Language Processing ( OreVar ) has begun to be used by security companies - for example SIEM ( OreVar Information and Event Management ) solutions. The more advanced of these solutions use AI and NLP to automatically sort the data in networks into high risk and low risk information. This enables security teams to focus on the attacks that have the potential to do real harm to the organization , and not become victims of attacks such as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Denial-of-service_attack" OreVar = "Denial-of-service attack" > Denial of Service ( OreVar ) < /a > , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Malware" OreVar = "Malware" > Malware < /a > and others.

< p > The simplest AI applications can be divided into two types: classifiers ( OreVar shiny then diamond" ) and controllers ( OreVar shiny then pick up" ) . Controllers do , however , also classify conditions before inferring actions , and therefore classification forms a central part of many AI systems. < a OreVar = OreDef ( mathematics ) " OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = OreDef ( mathematics ) " > Classifiers < /a > are functions that use < a OreVar = "/wiki/Pattern_matching" OreVar = "Pattern matching" > pattern matching < /a > to determine a closest match. They can be tuned according to examples , making them very attractive for use in AI. These examples are known as observations or patterns. In supervised learning , each pattern belongs to a certain predefined class. A class can be seen as a decision that has to be made. All the observations combined with their class labels are known as a data set. When a new observation is received , that observation is classified based on previous experience. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Classifiers_216-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Classifiers-216" > &#91 ; 210&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

tub < /span > < span OreVar = "reference-text" > Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems , or from non-pattern perturbations. Some systems are so brittle that changing a single adversarial pixel predictably induces misclassification.

< p > Historically , projects such as the Cyc knowledge base ( OreVar ) and the massive Japanese < a OreVar = "/wiki/Fifth_generation_computer" OreVar = "Fifth generation computer" > Fifth Generation Computer Systems < /a > initiative ( OreVar ) attempted to cover the breadth of human cognition. These early projects failed to escape the limitations of non-quantitative symbolic logic models and , in retrospect , greatly underestimated the difficulty of cross-domain AI. Nowadays , the vast majority of current AI researchers work instead on tractable "narrow AI" applications ( OreVar as medical diagnosis or automobile navigation ) . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-contemporary_agi_146-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-contemporary_agi-146" > &#91 ; 143&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Many researchers predict that such "narrow AI" work in different individual domains will eventually be incorporated into a machine with < a OreVar = "/wiki/Artificial_general_intelligence" OreVar = "Artificial general intelligence" > artificial general intelligence < /a > ( OreVar ) , combining most of the narrow skills mentioned in this article and at some point even exceeding human ability in most or all these areas. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-General_intelligence_19-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-General_intelligence-19" > &#91 ; 19&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< p > The relationship between automation and employment is complicated. While automation eliminates old jobs , it also creates new jobs through micro-economic and macro-economic effects. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-384" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-384" > &#91 ; 373&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Unlike previous waves of automation , many middle-class jobs may be eliminated by artificial intelligence ; < i > < a OreVar = "/wiki/The_Economist" OreVar = "The Economist" > The Economist < /a > < /i > states that "the worry that AI could do to white-collar jobs what steam power did to blue-collar ones during the Industrial Revolution" is "worth taking seriously". < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-385" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-385" > &#91 ; 374&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Subjective estimates of the risk vary widely ; for example , Michael Osborne and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Carl_Benedikt_Frey" OreVar = "Carl Benedikt Frey" > Carl Benedikt Frey < /a > estimate 47% of U.S. jobs are at "high risk" of potential automation , while an OECD report classifies only 9% of U.S. jobs as "high risk". < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-386" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-386" > &#91 ; 375&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-387" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-387" > &#91 ; 376&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-388" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-388" > &#91 ; 377&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Jobs at extreme risk range from paralegals to fast food cooks , while job demand is likely to increase for care-related professions ranging from personal healthcare to the clergy. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-389" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-389" > &#91 ; 378&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Author < a OreVar = OreDef ( author ) " OreVar = "Martin Ford ( OreVar ) " > Martin Ford < /a > and others go further and argue that many jobs are routine , repetitive and ( OreVar an AI ) predictable ; Ford warns that these jobs may be automated in the next couple of decades , and that many of the new jobs may not be "accessible to people with average capability" , even with retraining. Economists point out that in the past technology has tended to increase rather than reduce total employment , but acknowledge that "we're in uncharted territory" with AI. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-guardian_jobs_debate_24-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-guardian_jobs_debate-24" > &#91 ; 24&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

< a OreVar = "#CITEREFGödel1951" > Gödel 1951 < /a > : in this lecture , < a OreVar = "/wiki/Kurt_G%C3%B6del" OreVar = "Kurt Gödel" > Kurt Gödel < /a > uses the incompleteness theorem to arrive at the following disjunction: ( OreVar ) the human mind is not a consistent finite machine , or ( OreVar ) there exist < a OreVar = "/wiki/Diophantine_equations" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Diophantine equations" > Diophantine equations < /a > for which it cannot decide whether solutions exist. Gödel finds ( OreVar ) implausible , and thus seems to have believed the human mind was not equivalent to a finite machine , i.e. , its power exceeded that of any finite machine. < p > In < a OreVar = "/wiki/Computer_science" OreVar = "Computer science" > computer science < /a > , < b > artificial intelligence < /b > ( OreVar b > AI < /b > ) , sometimes called < b > machine intelligence < /b > , is < a OreVar = "/wiki/Intelligence" OreVar = "Intelligence" > intelligence < /a > demonstrated by < a OreVar = "/wiki/Machine" OreVar = "Machine" > machines < /a > , in contrast to the < b > natural intelligence < /b > displayed by < a OreVar = "/wiki/Human_intelligence" OreVar = "Human intelligence" > humans < /a > and < a OreVar = "/wiki/Animal_cognition" OreVar = "Animal cognition" > animals < /a > . Leading AI textbooks define the field as the study of " < a OreVar = "/wiki/Intelligent_agent" OreVar = "Intelligent agent" > intelligent agents < /a > ": any device that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of successfully achieving its goals. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1" > &#91 ; 1&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > Colloquially , the term "artificial intelligence" is often used to describe machines ( OreVar computers ) that mimic "cognitive" functions that humans associate with the < a OreVar = "/wiki/Human_mind" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Human mind" > human mind < /a > , such as "learning" and "problem solving". < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig20092_2-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig20092-2" > &#91 ; 2&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

Clark also presents factual data indicating the improvements of AI since 2012 supported by lower error rates in image processing tasks. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-:0_53-0" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-:0-53" > &#91 ; < p > The long-term economic effects of AI are uncertain. A survey of economists showed disagreement about whether the increasing use of robots and AI will cause a substantial increase in long-term < a OreVar = "/wiki/Unemployment" OreVar = "Unemployment" > unemployment < /a > , but they generally agree that it could be a net benefit , if < a OreVar = "/wiki/Productivity" OreVar = "Productivity" > productivity < /a > gains are < a OreVar = "/wiki/Redistribution_of_income_and_wealth" OreVar = "Redistribution of income and wealth" > redistributed < /a > . < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-413" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-413" > &#91 ; 401&#93 ; < /a > < /sup > A February 2020 European Union white paper on artificial intelligence advocated for artificial intelligence for economic benefits , including "improving healthcare ( OreVar making diagnosis more precise , enabling better prevention of diseases ) , increasing the efficiency of farming , contributing to climate change mitigation and adaptation , [and] improving the efficiency of production systems through predictive maintenance" , while acknowledging potential risks. < sup OreVar = "cite_ref-:1_290-1" OreVar = "reference" > < a OreVar = "#cite_note-:1-290" > &#91 ; 279&#93 ; < /a > < /sup >

Weizenbaum was also bothered that AI researchers ( OreVar some philosophers ) were willing to view the human mind as nothing more than a computer program ( OreVar position now known as < a OreVar = "/wiki/Computationalism" OreVar = "mw-redirect" OreVar = "Computationalism" > computationalism < /a > ) .
